 the same things I said about the trees apply here.  The viral sequences kept evolving from the point of common ancestry between the victim and the source such that none of them were identical to each other or to the ancestral sequences.  Of course, if you could have sampled back at the exact time of transmission (and if that transmitted sample was homogenous), you could have captured the ancestral sequence. But regardless, the patterns of variation among the victim and putative source sequences are sufficient to make the case, despite the accumulation of changes since the common ancestral sequence.\x3cbr /\x3e\x3cbr /\x3eI\x26#39;m not clear about your thinking on the outgroups, but I\x26#39;ll just add that those again are a choice (a part of taxon sampling).  So I\x26#39;d hesitate to call any particular sample of outgroups \x26#39;correct\x26#39;.', 'timestamp': '1474609925910', 'permalink': 'http://for-the-love-of-trees.blogspot.com/2016/09/the-ancestors-are-not-among-us.html?showComment\x3d1474609925910#c1681371878740922669', 'author': {'name': 'Stacey Smith', 'avatarUrl': '//lh3.googleusercontent.com/-zOreCSGlGZc/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAABW4/tqP7G40RLAI/s35-c/photo.jpg', 'profileUrl': 'https://www.blogger.com/profile/00476159407653766652'}, 'displayTime': 'September 22, 2016 at 10:52 PM', 'deleteclass': 'item-control blog-admin pid-192253648'}, {'id': '8918083161619097427', 'parentId': '1905558367326450940', 'body': 'I use \x26#39;base of the tree\x26#39; and \x26#39;basal nodes\x26#39; in my blog as an attempt to show these reasonable and informative uses.  But as I said, in my experience, the term basal usually misapplied (either to taxa / lineages or branches that are not actually an internal branch near the root).  These are the uses that carry strong connotations (e.g. about some taxa being \x26#39;lower\x26#39; or \x26#39;less evolved\x26#39;) and that allow ladder-of-progress misconceptions to persist.  I certainly don\x26#39;t expect basal to disappear -- 